{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014LgteRsAiHCkSdnjnJk237","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, there's a problem: `setUserClearedMatch` is defined AFTER `selectMatch` but used in `selectMatch`. Let me check — `setUserClearedMatch` is defined as part of `const [userClearedMatch, setUserClearedMatch] = useState(false);`. I'm putting `selectMatch` before the `useState` for `userClearedMatch`.\n\nLet me re-read the file to see the order.\n\nActually, in React, `useState` returns a stable setter function. And `useCallback` captures the setter at callback creation time. Since both `setUserClearedMatch` and `setActiveMatch` are stable state setter functions from `useState`, they're available throughout the component body regardless of declaration order... Wait, no. In JavaScript, `const` declarations are not hoisted (they have a temporal dead zone). \n\nRight, so I'll hit a ReferenceError if I try to use `setUserClearedMatch` before it's declared. I need to reorder things so the state declaration comes before the callback that uses it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":375,"cache_read_input_tokens":81681,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":375},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"73651d8d-ca1a-4f9e-b9b7-f2b958b23ec2","uuid":"52632236-1da3-4c6c-b8ce-ea090beb9a55"}
